@node Arguments "CLI Arguments"

@{fg fill} Below is a list of SFR CLI Keywords with their Arguments. SFR will not
 interpret an argument if its keyword is missing. I.e You cannot just type
 the argument 100 without typing the keyword RANGE_START for example as
 other keywords might use a 100 argument. Thus, SFR would have an hard time
 differentiating everything.

 You can use more than one keyword/argument set. Example:

   SFR FILE_TYPENAME FSS RANGE_START 2 RANGE_STOP 155

 Keywords and Arguments must be UPPERCASE. As a result of you Typing in
 uppercase SFR does not get clogged up with conversion code, opening of
 the Utility.Library, etc.

@{fg shine} CLI Arguments@{fg text}

 DEVICE_LOADFROM DeviceName

 This tells SFR which device to use, with the drawer LanguageGUI, for
 Loading operations. For example. SFR DEVICE_LOADFROM WORK: tells SFR
 that your Language and Speech Files should be found in the drawer
 WORK:LanguageGUI.

 DeviceName can be:

       DH0:  DH1:  DH2:  DH3:  WORK: or LGUI:   Hard Drive Device/Partition.

                     DF0:  DF1:  DF2: or DF3:   Floppy Drives.


 FILE_TYPENAME Type

 Type can be:    FNS - This will make the file to check be FNSpeech.Lgui

                 FSS - This will make the file to check be FSSpeech.Lgui

 If this argument is not used, or used but not with a valid Type, the file
 to check will be FNSpeech.Lgui by default.


 RANGE_START Number

 Number is the starting position of your range. If you are Decreasing,
 RANGE_START should be in the range of 2 upto 1499. If you are Increasing,
 RANGE_START should be in the range of 1 upto 1499.


 RANGE_STOP Number

 Number is the end position of your range. If you are Decreasing, RANGE_STOP
 should be in the range of 3 upto 1500. If you are Increasing, RANGE_STOP
 should be in the range of 2 upto 1500.


 INCREASE YES/NO

 Use INCREASE YES if you want to Increase and INCREASE NO if you want to
 Decrease.
@{fg fill}
 Default values are used when a Keyword/Argument is not used/entered.@{fg fill}
@{fg shine}
 General Information@{fg text}

 * Your range does not have to be complete. For example. RANGE_START 1
   RANGE STOP 100 (a range of 100) Increase does not mean SWSTBA 1 to 100
   have to be in your speech file. Because SFR simply checks a SWSTBA to
   see if it is in your range, before increasing, you could just have
   SWSTBA 1, 3 and 77 for example. In this case SWSTBA 1, 3 and 77 would
   be increased to 2, 4 and 78 respectively.

   At the moment SFR only Increases or Decreases by 1. A future version
   would hopefully give you an option to increase or decrease by more.

 * Check for double SWSTBA values. For example. If your range was 1 to 2
   Increase and you had SWSTBA 1, 2 and 3. 1 would be increased to 2.
   2 would be Increased to 3. 3 would be left alone as it is not in your
   range. Thus, you would have SWSTBA values 1, 2 and 3 now as 2, 3 and 3.

   A future version would hopefully check for double values.
@endnode

